  "prompt": "Is it true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime?",
  "response": "No, it is not true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime.\n\nWhile chickenpox used to be very common, it is not a certainty anymore. There are two main reasons for this:\n\n*   **Vaccination:** The chickenpox vaccine (varicella vaccine) is highly effective in preventing chickenpox. Many children and adults are now vaccinated, significantly reducing the likelihood of contracting the disease.\n\n*   **Exposure:** Even before the vaccine, not everyone contracted chickenpox. Some people may have had a very mild or asymptomatic case, and therefore would not even realize they had chickenpox.\n\n**Key points:**\n\n*   Chickenpox vaccination is the best way to prevent chickenpox.\n*   If you've been vaccinated or have already had chickenpox, you are typically immune.\n*   Not everyone will get chickenpox in their lifetime, especially with the widespread use of the vaccine.\n",
